            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " scratches the itch of a classic JRPG very well and it fits the genre like a glove, with certain additions that make it a unique experience and is definitely a fun pickup for fans of the genre, with its strengths being firmly found in the pragmatic gameplay parts of the game and in its visuals. However, the faulty aspects in characters and worldbuilding truly demonstrates how important they are for an initially engaging experience - the very first hook for RPGs, the thing that gets people to continue paying attention, should be their characters. Engagement leads the player into wanting to see how they would advance in their lives and through the challenges presented, but it is honestly hard to root for these characters at the start and that really diminishes the enjoyment of the game for those that appreciate the story aspect of a JRPG more so than the gameplay aspects. Smile a little more, will you, Aldo?",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
